Name: John Smith
Age: 67
Gender: Male
Occupation: Retired
Ethnicity: Caucasian
Past Medical History: Hypertension, hyperlipidemia, benign prostatic hyperplasia (BPH)

Case Report:
John Smith is a 67-year-old Caucasian male who presented to his primary care physician with complaints of difficulty urinating and blood in his urine. Upon further evaluation, he was found to have an enlarged prostate and underwent a biopsy which revealed adenocarcinoma of the prostate. His prostate-specific antigen (PSA) level was 12 ng/mL.

Further imaging studies revealed no evidence of metastatic disease. He was referred to a urologist for further management. After discussing treatment options, he opted for robotic-assisted laparoscopic prostatectomy. The surgery was successful, and pathology revealed a Gleason score of 7 (3+4) with negative surgical margins.

He was then referred to an oncologist for adjuvant radiation therapy. He completed a course of radiation therapy without any significant side effects.

Follow-up PSA levels were monitored closely and remained undetectable. John continues to be monitored by his urologist and oncologist regularly for any signs of recurrence.

Age: 62
Gender: Male
Occupation: Retired
Ethnicity: Caucasian
Past Medical History: Hypertension, hyperlipidemia, and benign prostatic hyperplasia

Case Report:
John Smith is a 62-year-old retired Caucasian male who presented to his primary care physician with complaints of difficulty urinating for the past few months. He also reported a decrease in the force of his urine stream and occasional blood in his urine. On physical examination, his prostate was enlarged and firm to the touch.

Further evaluation with a prostate-specific antigen (PSA) blood test and a transrectal ultrasound-guided biopsy revealed a diagnosis of prostate adenocarcinoma. The biopsy results showed a Gleason score of 7 (3+4), indicating an intermediate-risk prostate cancer.

Name: John Smith
Age: 65
Gender: Male
Occupation: Retired
Ethnicity: Caucasian
Past Medical History: Hypertension, hyperlipidemia, benign prostatic hyperplasia (BPH)

Chief Complaint:
John Smith presented to his primary care physician with complaints of difficulty urinating and blood in his urine. He reported feeling fatigued and experiencing back pain.

History of Present Illness:
John reported that he had been experiencing urinary symptoms for several months, including hesitancy, dribbling, and a weak urine stream. He also noticed blood in his urine on several occasions. He had been taking medication for BPH, but it did not seem to be helping. Additionally, he had been experiencing fatigue and back pain, which he attributed to his age.

Physical Examination:
On physical examination, John appeared fatigued and had a slightly enlarged prostate on digital rectal examination. There were no other significant findings on examination.

Diagnostic Tests:
John underwent a prostate-specific antigen (PSA) test, which was significantly elevated at 25 ng/mL (normal range: 0-4 ng/mL). A biopsy confirmed the diagnosis of prostate cancer, with a Gleason score of 7 (3+4).
